intrinsic=comes from inside, e.g., motivation to learn
overhead=ongoing extra cost; called overhead because it sits “above” direct work, e.g., rent, admin salaries
retention=keeping customers over time, e.g., users who keep using the product
verge=edge; point just before change, e.g., on the verge of success
market fit=product matches real customer need, e.g., users adopt it naturally
sticky growth=old users stay while new users add up
persevere=keep trying despite difficulty, e.g., continue after failure
actionable metrics=measurements that guide next steps, e.g., drop in daily active users triggers feature fix
AAA=Actionable, Accessible, Auditable — metrics that guide decisions, easy to access, verifiable
Actionable=metric guiding decisions, e.g., drop in users triggers fix
Accessible=easy to get, e.g., team can see dashboard anytime
Auditable=verifiable, e.g., data can be checked for accuracy
vanity metrics=looks good but no insight, e.g., total downloads without engagement
vanity=pride in appearance or status, e.g., showing off wealth
target early adopters=reach via niche channels, direct outreach, demos, e.g., tech forums or beta invites
leap of faith=risky step based on belief, e.g., launch untested product to learn
innovation accounting=measure progress in learning, e.g., track validated learning, not just revenue
identity=seen through actions and choices, e.g., founder becomes “builds startups” rather than just “entrepreneur”
retention rate=percentage of users staying over time, e.g., 80% keep using app after month